<h1>Random sample size</h1>




<h3>Why use random sample size?</h3>

The main idea behind sequential statistics is that two samples of the same
size generated by the same underlying process can have different
information content depending on the particular numerical values
observed. So in sequential statistics we collect out sample
<i>sequentially</i> i.e., 

<blockquote>
at each step we look at the sample collected so far, and decide
if it already contains enough information. If so, we stop. Else, we
observe more data, and this continues at each step until the sample
becomes informative enough.
</blockquote>

<p>Obviously the sample collected by this algorithm is of a random size,
its size being the value of the stopping time used. The main reason behind
using sequential statistics is that we can achieve goals with random
sample sizes that cannot be achieved with any fixed sample size. Here is
one example.
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#995555"></td>
   <td>
   <b>Example:</b> 
   
   Suppose that
   
   <blockquote>
   X<sub>1</sub>,X<sub>2</sub>,... are iid N(&mu;,&sigma;),
   </blockquote>
   
   both &mu; and &sigma; being unknown. We want to construct a 5% CI for
   &mu;. We also want the length of our CI to be always less than 10. No
   fixed sample size can achieve this. However, it is possible to achieve
   this using random sample size. We shall prove this in a sequence of
   exercises below.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<h4>Why fixed sample size fails here</h4>

First consider a simple "proof", which unfortunately is wrong.
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise SEQ4.1:</font></b> 
   
   Consider the following argument:
   
   <blockquote>
   Let n be any fixed sample size. Let 
                                       <img src=
                                       "resources/statinf2/xbar.png"
                                       align=top>
                                       
                                        and s be sample
   mean and standard deviation, resp, of the sample of size n. Then we know
   that the the CI
   
   <blockquote>
   (
    <img src=
    "resources/statinf2/xbar.png"
    align=top>
    
    -ts/sqrt(n), 
                 <img src=
                 "resources/statinf2/xbar.png"
                 align=top>
                 
                  + t s/sqrt(n))
   </blockquote>
   
   where t is the appropriate cut-off point of t-distribution has the
   shortest possible expected length. Now, its length is 
   
   <blockquote>
   L = 2t s/sqrt(n),
   </blockquote>
   
   which is supported on the the entire positive real line, since
   s<sup>2</sup> is a 
                      <img src="resources/statinf2/chisqd.png" align=top>
                      
                       random variable. So P(L &gt; 10)  &gt; 0.
   Since this is the shortest possible expected length CI, hence no other CI
   can do better. Hence the result. 
   </blockquote>
   
   Why is this not a correct argument?
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
A correct argument is as follows (informally)

<blockquote>
Let &mu;<sub>1</sub> and &mu;<sub>2</sub> be any two fixed
numbers. Even they are far apart, the two distributions

<blockquote>
N(&mu;<sub>1</sub>, &sigma;) and
N(&mu;<sub>2</sub>,&sigma;)
</blockquote>

become almost indistinguishable as &sigma; goes to infinity. Thus, even
if some fixed n can produce a CI meeting our criteria for some given
&sigma;, it will fail if we increase &sigma; sufficiently. So no fixed
n can achieve our goal uniformly for all &sigma;.
</blockquote>

The following exercises will make this rigorous.

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise SEQ4.2:</font></b> 
   
   Show that if &delta; 
                        <img src=
                        "resources/statinf2/rarrow.png"
                        align=middle>
                        
                         0, then 
   
   <blockquote>
   
   <img src=
   "resources/statinf2/int.png"
   align=middle>
   
    | &phi;(x,&delta;)-&phi;(x,0)| dx 
                                      <img src=
                                      "resources/statinf2/rarrow.png"
                                      align=middle>
                                      
                                       0.
   </blockquote>
   
   [Hint: Fix &epsilon;  &gt;  0. Chop off tails (b,
                                                    <img src=
                                                    "resources/statinf2/inf.png"
                                                    align=top>
                                                    
                                                    ) and
   (-
     <img src=
     "resources/statinf2/inf.png"
     align=top>
     
     ,a) with probability &epsilon;/3. Use the fact that over the
   compact interval normal density is uniformly continuous.]
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise SEQ4.3:</font></b> 
   
   Fix any &mu;<sub>1</sub>, &mu;<sub>2</sub>. Show that as &sigma;
   
   <img src=
   "resources/statinf2/rarrow.png"
   align=middle>
   
    
    <img src=
    "resources/statinf2/inf.png"
    align=top>
    
    ,
   
   <blockquote>
   
   <img src=
   "resources/statinf2/int.png"
   align=middle>
   
   |&phi;(x,&mu;<sub>1</sub>,&sigma;)-
   &phi;(x,&mu;<sub>2</sub>,&sigma;)|
   dx 
      <img src=
      "resources/statinf2/rarrow.png"
      align=middle>
      
       0..
   </blockquote>
   
   [Hint: Use the last exercise, after suitably defining &delta;.]
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise SEQ4.4:</font></b> 
   
   This is just like the last exercise, but for general sample size n. Fix
   &mu;<sub>1</sub>, &mu;<sub>2</sub>. Show that as &sigma; 
                                                            <img src=
                                                            "resources/statinf2/rarrow.png"
                                                            align=middle>
                                                            
                                                            
   
   <img src=
   "resources/statinf2/inf.png"
   align=top>
   
   ,
   
   <blockquote>
   
   <img src=
   "resources/statinf2/int.png"
   align=middle>
   
   ...
      <img src=
      "resources/statinf2/int.png"
      align=middle>
      
      |&phi;(x<sub>1</sub>,...,
   X<sub>n</sub>,&mu;<sub>1</sub>,&sigma;)
   -&phi;(x<sub>1</sub>,...,x<sub>n</sub>,&mu;<sub>2</sub>,&sigma;)|
