   </blockquote>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
Now we shall use all these to complete the proof. Suppose that, if
possible, there is some n and a CI, (L,U), based on a sample of size n,
such that

<blockquote>
U-L 
    <img src=
    "resources/statinf2/leq.png"
    align=top>
    
     10<br>
and<br>
P(L &lt; &mu;  &lt; U) 
                       <img src=
                       "resources/statinf2/geq.png"
                       align=top>
                       
                        0.95 for all &mu;,&sigma;.
</blockquote>

We shall arrive at a contradiction from these. Choose &mu;<sub>1</sub>,
&mu;<sub>2</sub> such that

<blockquote>
&mu;<sub>2</sub>-&mu;<sub>1</sub>  &gt;  10.
</blockquote>

Consider the two events

<blockquote>
A = {L  &lt;  &mu;<sub>1</sub>  &lt; U}<br>
B = {L &lt;  &mu;<sub>2</sub>  &lt;  U}
</blockquote>

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise SEQ4.6:</font></b> 
   
   Show that A, B are disjoint. By the last exercise we know that for
   sufficiently large &sigma; 
   
   <blockquote>
   |P(A; &mu;<sub>1</sub>, &sigma;) - P(B;
   &mu;<sub>2</sub>,&sigma;)|  &lt;  0.01, say.
   </blockquote>
   
   Hence conclude that for such a &sigma;, 
   
   <blockquote>
   P(B;&mu;<sub>1</sub>,&sigma;)  &gt;  0.9
   </blockquote>
   
   and that
   
   <blockquote>
   P(A 
       <img src="resources/statinf2/union.png">
        B; &mu;<sub>1</sub>,&sigma;))  &gt;  1,
   </blockquote>
   
   a contradiction.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   



<h3>How random sample size saves the day.</h3>

Random sample size means sampling until a stopping time is reached. A
stopping time time is a strategy telling us when to stop. The following
strategy (called <i>Stein's rule</i>) lets us achieve our aim.

<p>
Fix some initial sample size m 
                               <img src=
                               "resources/statinf2/geq.png"
                               align=top>
                               
                                2. Draw m samples

<blockquote>
X<sub>1</sub>,...,X<sub>m</sub>
</blockquote>

Let 
    <img src=
    "resources/statinf2/xbar.png"
    align=top>
    
    <sub>m</sub> and s<sub>m</sub> be sample mean and variance,
respectively. Consider the usual CI based on t-distribution:

<blockquote>
(
 <img src=
 "resources/statinf2/xbar.png"
 align=top>
 
 <sub>m</sub> - t*s<sub>m</sub>/sqrt(m),

<img src=
"resources/statinf2/xbar.png"
align=top>

<sub>m</sub>+ t*s<sub>m</sub>/sqrt(m)
 
</blockquote>

Its length, i.e., 2*t*s<sub>m</sub>/sqrt(m)  &lt; 10, then stop. Else find
n such that 

<blockquote>
2*t*s<sub>m</sub>/sqrt(n)  &lt;  10.
</blockquote>

(Note that this n is random, since it depends on s<sub>m</sub>). Draw n-m
more samples and report the following CI

<blockquote>
(
 <img src=
 "resources/statinf2/xbar.png"
 align=top>
 
 <sub>n</sub> - t*s<sub>m</sub>/sqrt(m),

<img src=
"resources/statinf2/xbar.png"
align=top>

<sub>n</sub>+ t*s<sub>m</sub>/sqrt(m)
 
</blockquote>

Here 
     <img src=
     "resources/statinf2/xbar.png"
     align=top>
     
     <sub>n</sub> is based on all the n samples. Observe that we
are still using the old s<sub>m</sub> and not s<sub>n</sub>. <p>

Clearly, this CI has length  &lt;  10, by construction.
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise SEQ4.7:</font></b> 
   
   Show that it is indeed a 95% CI.
   [Hint: First show that
   (X<sub>1</sub>-
                  <img src=
                  "resources/statinf2/xbar.png"
                  align=top>
                  
                  <sub>m</sub>,...,X<sub>m</sub>-
                                                 <img src=
                                                 "resources/statinf2/xbar.png"
                                                 align=top>
                                                 
                                                 <sub>m</sub>)
   is independent
   of 
      <img src=
      "resources/statinf2/xbar.png"
      align=top>
      
      <sub>n</sub>.]
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   



<h4>Pilot surveys</h4>

A close kin to the above approach is that of a pilot survey, which is a
simple form of sequential statistical method. Here we start by drawing a
small sample, called the pilot sample. Based on this we form crude
estimates about the noise level present in the data, and how much sample
is required to achieve some specified level of accuracy. Then we perform
the main survey to collect these many samples. 


